{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523454"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13900"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.12,0.15,0.16,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1004"},{"type":"tags","id":"2904"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18104"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of a rapidly expanding growth over her left upper gum margin. She has also noted fatigue, night sweats, and weight loss during this one-month period. She has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Her regular medications, which she has been on for four years, are lercanidipine and rosuvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 115/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Examination of the oral cavity reveals a firm, purple-coloured mass on the left upper gum margin (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 85 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 3 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 57 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 0.4 x 10^9/L (2-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 156 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 30 mL/min/1.73m^2 (\u226590)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 560 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood smear also reveals a high number of blast cells present: 2 x 10^9/L (\u0026lt;1), 66%\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for the image shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myeloid sarcoma","Gingival hyperplasia related to lercanidipine","Burkitt lymphoma","Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma","Chronic myeloid leukaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe elderly patient presents with one month of constitutional symptoms and was found to have pancytopenia, elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), and a high proportion of blast cells in the peripheral blood (66%). This strongly suggests an acute leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyeloid sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It is a rare manifestation of acute myeloid leukaemia (AML) that presents as a solid tumour of myeloblasts outside the bone marrow. Myeloid sarcoma can occur before, simultaneously with, or after the diagnosis of AML. The presence of blasts in the peripheral blood and the gum lesion highly suggest this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of myeloid sarcoma would require further investigations, including a bone marrow biopsy to assess for AML and a biopsy of the gum lesion to confirm the myeloid origin of the cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGingival hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a known side effect of calcium channel blockers. However, it typically presents as a generalised gingival overgrowth rather than a localised mass. Moreover, the systemic symptoms and abnormal blood results make this diagnosis unlikely, and the patient has been on these drugs for years, so an abrupt change due to these drugs are even less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBurkitt lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an aggressive B-cell lymphoma that can present with rapidly growing masses, including in the oral cavity. However, it typically affects younger individuals and would not explain the blast cells seen in the blood film.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse large B-cell lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an aggressive B-cell lymphoma that can present with extranodal masses. However, it is a lymphoproliferative disorder and would not present with a high percentage of blast cells in the peripheral blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0can rarely present with the extramedullary disease. However, involvement of the oral cavity would be highly unusual. The acute presentation and high peripheral blood blast percentage are more consistent with AML and myeloid sarcoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myeloid sarcoma is an extramedullary manifestation of acute myeloid leukaemia, presenting as a solid tumour of myeloblasts.","Myeloid sarcoma can occur before, during, or after the diagnosis of acute myeloid leukaemia."],"references":["Almond LM, Charalampakis M, Ford SJ, Gourevitch D, Desai A. Myeloid Sarcoma: Presentation, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Clin Lymphoma Myeloma Leuk. 2017;17(5):263-267. doi:10.1016/j.clml.2017.02.027","Loscocco GG, Vannucchi AM. Myeloid sarcoma: more and less than a distinct entity. Ann Hematol. 2023;102(8):1973-1984. doi:10.1007/s00277-023-05288-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20836"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20836"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DWI8w2XY50bwig0S7EUFLNIWlZLuAY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DWI8w2XY50bwig0S7EUFLNIWlZLuAY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-30T21:39:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T21:40:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58306"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"